A Study of the Opioid Epidemic in the United States¶

DSC540 Final Project¶

Amal Almansour, Jordan Bickelhaupt, Jason Elengical & Yianni Mercer¶

Introduction¶

The increasing number of overdose deaths in the U.S. is an urgent issue. The research we will be conducting will be an attempt to leverage data analysis and machine learning techniques in order to identify potential solutions, and most of all raise awareness

The number of drug overdose deaths increased by nearly 5% from 2018 to 2019 and has quadrupled since 19991. Over 70% of the 70,630 deaths in 2019 involved an opioid. CDC

Datasets Used¶

1) U.S. Opiate Prescriptions dataset contains a subset of data from The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services

- Sub-datasets included 'Prescriber Info', 'Opioid Drug Descriptions' and 'Overdose counts by State'  
- This dataset assisted in the development of a dataframe which summarized specific prescriptions of drugs for each state, combined with the total deaths for the same state(s)

2) Deaths Casued by Opioids by State (1999-2014)

- Basic dataset that totals the number of opioid deaths in each state for each years, beginning in 1999, up until 2014.

3) Summary File of Connecticut Medicare

- Data containing information on speciifc counties within the State of CT, explaning the rampant metrics of opioid prescriptions being prescribed each year, along with the number of drug-related overdoses in the same year

Research Questions¶

1) How likely a prescriber is going to prescribe an opioids medicine based on prescribed medicine per year?¶

Built a classification model which will learn from the prescribers who prescribed opioids, to predict the likelihood of a prescriber to prescribe opioids.**

2) What states should we look out for when it comes to opioid overdose?¶

Performing random forest regression with different visualizations.

3) Where are the most rampant areas of Opioid Prescribing Rates in Connecticut?¶

By performing thorough exploratory data analysis on data that provided geographical information (Connecticut) we were able to focus our initial understanding of the Opioid Drug and related Death Problem on specific areas of the State of Connecticut

4) Can we predict the number of state level deaths caused by opioid related overdoses?¶

Beginning with the prescriber dataset, we summarized this into a Pandas GroupBy Dataframe for each state, summing the total of each type of opioid that was described (and removing columns like Gender, Credentials and Opioid prescriber).  We then combined this dataset with the overdoses dataset, using the state as index, allowing us to view the total sums of the types of drugs each state prescribes and the total number of deaths each state has due to opioids.  From here, a series of Random Forest Regression models were developed to predict the total number of deaths due to Opioid overdoses

Machine Learning Methods Used¶

For the prescribers information dataset, we used,¶

Logistic Regression

Gradient Boosting Classifier

Random Forest Classifier

Gaussian Naive Bayes

Decision Tree Classifier

Adaboost Classifier

Voting Classifier (Soft and Hard voting)

For the Overdose dataset, we used,¶

Random Forest Regression

Support Vector Regression

For the dataset that was derived from the above two, we used,¶

Random Forest Regression

    -- Tuned hyperparameters with GridSearchCV

import pandas as pd

U.S. Opiate Prescriptions/Overdoses on Kaggle has a subset of the data from cms.gov: Medicare Provider Charge Data.¶

The data decription as written on Kaggle is as follows:¶

  • NPI unique National Provider Identifier number
  • Gender - (M/F)
  • State - U.S. State by abbreviation
  • Credentials - set of initials indicative of medical degree
  • Specialty - description of type of medicinal practice
  • A long list of drugs with numeric values indicating the total number of prescriptions written for the year by that individual
  • Opioid.Prescriber - a boolean label indicating whether or not that individual prescribed opiate drugs more than 10 times in the year

In [220]:



     


# function that generates the model, predicts test data and prints confusion matrix. 
def fit_predict_score_train(name,clf):
    clf.fit(X_train, np.ravel(y_train))
    classes = ['No Opioid', 'Opioid']
    predicted = clf.predict(X_train)
    
    # training data:
    print("Training data:")
    # Confusion matrix
    confusion_matrix =  pd.crosstab(index=np.ravel(y_train), columns=predicted.ravel(), rownames=['Expected'], colnames=['Predicted'])
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix, annot=True, square=False, fmt='', cbar=False)
    accuracy = np.round(metrics.accuracy_score(y_train , predicted),3)
    plt.title(name + " " + str(accuracy), fontsize = 15)
    plt.show()
    print (metrics.classification_report(y_train,predicted, target_names=classes))



     















In [221]:



     


def fit_predict_score_test(name,clf):
    clf.fit(X_train, np.ravel(y_train))
    classes = ['No Opioid', 'Opioid']
    predicted1 = clf.predict(X_test)
    # testing data
    print("Testing data:")
    # Confusion matrix
    confusion_matrix =  pd.crosstab(index=np.ravel(y_test), columns=predicted1.ravel(), rownames=['Expected'], colnames=['Predicted'])
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix, annot=True, square=False, fmt='', cbar=False)
    accuracy = np.round(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test , predicted1),3)
    plt.title(name + " " + str(accuracy), fontsize = 15)
    plt.show()
    print (metrics.classification_report(y_test,predicted1, target_names=classes))

  • Precision is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the total predicted positive observations.
    • 

  • Recall is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the all observations in actual class - yes.
    • 

  • F1 Score is the weighted average of Precision and Recall.  
    •

Voting Classifier¶
The idea behind the VotingClassifier is to combine conceptually different machine learning classifiers and use a majority vote or the average predicted probabilities (soft vote) to predict the class labels.

Such a classifier can be useful for a set of equally well performing models in order to balance out their individual weaknesses.











Let's create 6 models, make predictions, and take the average of these predictions to come with a hard voting classifier solution.¶
For each model,¶
    

  • We are using a cross_val_score (cv=5) to get the accuracy.
    • 

  • We are getting classifcation reports for the data without performing cross_val_score to compare the accuracy.
    • 












Soft Voting:¶










In [194]:



     


clf1 = linear_model.LogisticRegression(C=1e5, solver='lbfgs', multi_class='auto', max_iter=1000)
clf2 = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=0)
clf3 = GaussianNB()
clf4 = AdaBoostClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=0)
clf5 = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0)
clf6 = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=0)

eclf = VotingClassifier(
    estimators=[('lr', clf1), ('rf', clf2), ('gnb', clf3), ('ada', clf4), ('dtree',clf5), ('gboost',clf6)],
    voting='soft')

for clf, label in zip([clf1, clf2, clf3, clf4, clf5, clf6, eclf], 
                      ['Logistic Regression', 'Random Forest', 'Naive Bayes', 'AdaBoost', 'Decision Tree', 'Gradient Boosting', 'Ensemble']):
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, scoring='accuracy', cv=5)
    print("Accuracy: %0.3f (+/- %0.3f) [%s]" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), label))
    fit_predict_score_train(label,clf)

Hard Voting:¶










In [225]:



     


clf1 = linear_model.LogisticRegression(C=1e5, solver='lbfgs', multi_class='auto', max_iter=1000)
clf2 = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=0)
clf3 = GaussianNB()
clf4 = AdaBoostClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=0)
clf5 = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0)
clf6 = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=1.0, max_depth=1, random_state=0)

eclf = VotingClassifier(
    estimators=[('lr', clf1), ('rf', clf2), ('gnb', clf3), ('ada', clf4), ('dtree',clf5), ('gboost',clf6)],
    voting='hard')

for clf, label in zip([clf1, clf2, clf3, clf4, clf5, clf6, eclf], 
                      ['Logistic Regression', 'Random Forest', 'Naive Bayes', 'AdaBoost', 'Decision Tree', 'Gradient Boosting', 'Ensemble']):
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, scoring='accuracy', cv=5)
    print("Accuracy: %0.3f (+/- %0.3f) [%s]" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), label))
    fit_predict_score_train(label,clf)

In [295]:



     


def evaluate(model, test_features, test_labels):
    predictions = model.predict(test_features)
    errors = abs(predictions - test_labels)
    mape = 100 * np.mean(errors / test_labels)
    accuracy = 100 - mape
    print('Model Performance')
    print('Average Error: {:0.4f} degrees.'.format(np.mean(errors)))
    print('Accuracy = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy))
    
    return accuracy

### Grid Search w/ Random Forest Regressor

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from pprint import pprint
# Create the parameter grid based on the results of random search 
param_grid = {
    'bootstrap': [True],
    'max_depth': [80, 90, 100, 110],
    'max_features': [2, 3],
    'min_samples_leaf': [3, 4, 5],
    'min_samples_split': [8, 10, 12],
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300, 1000]
}

n_estimators= [100, 200, 300, 1000]
max_features= [2, 3]

# Instantiate the grid search model
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator = rfr, param_grid = param_grid, 
                          cv = 3, n_jobs = -1, verbose = 2)

# Fit the grid search to the data
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

grid_search.best_params_

def evaluate(model, test_features, test_labels):
    predictions = model.predict(test_features)
    errors = abs(predictions - test_labels)
    mape = 100 * np.mean(errors / test_labels)
    accuracy = 100 - mape
    print('Model Performance')
    print('Average Error: {:0.4f} degrees.'.format(np.mean(errors)))
    print('Accuracy = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy))
    
    return accuracy

best_grid = grid_search.best_estimator_
grid_accuracy = evaluate(best_grid, X_test, y_test)

rfr_best_grid_pred_train = best_grid.predict(X_train)

rfr_best_grid_pred_test = best_grid.predict(X_test)

#rmse of rfr w/ gridsearchcv TRAIN
rfr_best_grid_rmse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train, rfr_best_grid_pred_train)
rt_rfr_best_grid_rmse_train = np.sqrt(rfr_best_grid_rmse_train)
rt_rfr_best_grid_rmse_train

#rmse of rfr w/ gridsearchcv TEST
rfr_best_grid_rmse_test = mean_squared_error(y_test, rfr_best_grid_pred_test)
rt_rfr_best_grid_rmse_test = np.sqrt(rfr_best_grid_rmse_test)
rt_rfr_best_grid_rmse_test

Discussion¶
This was a significant improvement from the baseline Random forest regressor with default parameters model, however the model is still not in a position where it should be used in governmental studies or programs.  Our group believes that more data should be collected on a county level of the USA to explicitly develop a model that can accurately predict the number of deaths each state may have due to opioid overdoses


More data implies either more reliable data that we can verify through either the CDC, or other state data portals.  Or more data could also imply different types of variables that provide information with respect to any drugs that are being prescribed in each state and county in the U.S. (i.e., individual observation for each person taking these prescribed medicines with demographic variables like gender, age, race, ethnicity, etc.)











Conclusion¶
    

  • All the 6 models and the ensembled models with soft and hard voting performed well and the accuracies were very close. All the models have high accuracy scores [90%-93%] on the testing data. That means, the models we built to predict and classify whether or not the prescriber will prescribe an opioid are working with above 90% accuracy score R2 [0.59-0.70].
    • 

  • States that we should look at are ones that are highly populated.
      

    • Such as New York and California
      • 

    

    • 

  • In order to accurately predict the number of deaths due to Opioid overdoses, more data needs to be collected before we can allow for any governmental agency or program to use similar models to justify additional resources being made available to each state (or county)
